author: etiennedi
message:
use io.ReadFull on deserializer

It uses a bufio.Reader (or a derivative thereof), but those aren't
guaranteed to read fully, as they are guaranteed to only ever produce a
single Read on the underlying Reader. So we need ReadFull to read twice,
when the original buffer has less than n bytes left.

This prevents a nil-pointer panic that showed as part of a flaky test.
The actual cause is described in:
https://github.com/semi-technologies/weaviate/issues/1872#issuecomment-1076357479

To assure the test is fixed you can run run

```go
go test -race -tags integrationTest -count 10 -run TestMemtableThreshold_Replace ./adapters/repos/db/lsmkv
```

which reliably failed before, but no longer does so with the fix.

fixes #1872

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-677: move to URI-style cross-ref structure

This was implemented through severeal commits that didn't apply to my
usual standards, i.e. staying non-breaking in between. I thus decided to
squash them all into a single commit to avoid reverting parts and end up
with a non-working state. The original commit messages were:

    gh-677: fix all existing tests, remove tests for keys package

    ... or remove those acceptance tests that are already tested at a
    unit test level.

    Since we have already removed the tests for the key packages and
    stubbed out their implementation, the removal of keys as outlined in
    #646 must happen immediately after.

    gh-677: make everything compile again

    gh-677: add Ref type with options to parse from and stringify into

    The intent is to clean up this models.SingleRef mess that is spread
    throughout the validation and database packages. This new type
    should be the only way to extract info about refs and can easily be
    parsed from the API values and back into the API values to make sure
    we have an easy way to use around the API without mixing up API
    design and business logic.

    gh-677: remove obsolete props from cref Model

    This currently breaks in quite a few places because we don't seem to
    have a good isolation between api constructs and internal
    constructs.  Most of the time this isolation happens through using
    schema datatypes when talking to the db connectors, however in this
    case the models.SingleRef seems to be widely used in both validation
    and even the janus connector. This unfortunately leads to a
    massively breaking change when changing the model. Next up we need
    to clean up the fallout.

    The original reason for even starting this change was that
    acceptance tests would fail with invalid uuid for $cref which is now
    indeed a URI, rather than a UUID.

    gh-677: fix some more tests

    gh-677: udpate url strucutre in imporeter and make it succeed

    This can be seen as some sort of a spike to figure out the happy
    path.  While the importer succeeds it currently breaks all kinds of
    tests and is in no way complete.

    However, we pulled some good learnings out of this and now know what
    parts are affected and what aren't.

    We should consider squashing this branch in the end, so we don't end
    up with individually breaking builds on our trunk.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-660 only query peer if user wants classes from this peer

Note: (copy paste form a code comment)

---
We cannot do an exact check of whether the user specified that
they wanted this class as part of their SelectProperties because
we would only find out the exact className after resolving this.
However, resolving a network ref is a) not the concern of this
particular database connector and b) exactly what we want to
avoid. The point of checking whether this class is desired is to
prevent unnecassary network requests if the user doesn't care
about this reference.

So instead, we can at least check if the user asked about any
classes from this particular peer. If not we can safely determine
that this particular network ref is not desired.
---

Additionally this commit includes a test file that I previously forgot
to commit and some refactoring on the janus connector
LocalGetClassResolve which was another massive method that has now been
split up a bit to make it more readable and extendable.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-644: (refactor) clean up mixed concerns in network package

The network packages has sub-packages for each new branch in the tree,
such as Get, GetMeta, aggregate, etc. However, while tyring to write a
component test for GetMeta, we learned that in fact some of the GetMeta
logic (and that of other subpackages as well) is not in fact in the
seemingly isolated packages, but rather mixed up in the network
(root) package.

This refactor commit moves those separate concerns into their individual
packages. To make sure we don't break anything a few component tests
were added, that assert the successful creation of the graphql schema.
Since this part was previously untested on anything other than a e2e
level, we discovered lots of edge cases that would lead to errors, e.g.:

- A peer with an empty schema could block the creation
- A peer with a class without properties would lead to errors in the
Aggregate package, which blocked the creation
- etc...

All errors we discovered through the new component test were fixed.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1358 don't use buffered channel in class batch writer

This could use to a situation where we would accept the cancel signal
while the buffer was still filled. This would in turn mean we terminate
the save operation with unsaved elements in the queue.

After discussion within the team, we don't see any reason for the
buffered channel (anymore), so we don't think we'll lose anything by
using a regular, unbuffered channel.

A new intergration test which uses a real `db.Repo` with the classifier
has been added as I could not reproduce the bug with a storage fake. I
still don't know what exactly it took to reproduce it, but I assume it
was a combination of timings that happen to be very present with a real
DB, but aren't present with the fake - although I added various delays
to the fake.

The new integration test had about a 50% failure rate prior to the fix,
but has now completed 100 subsequent runs succesfully. This makes me
reasonably confident that this indeed closes #1358.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1069 on deduping ignore complete jobs

A job might already be marked as complete, but when checking references
we might come across the same job again, then missing it in our nested
cache. As a result, we're now ignoring completed jobs. This leads to an
additional lookup (but not request) in some cases, but prevents an
impossible to resolve situation in others.

Note: The lookup is not yet ideal, as we seem to overwrite elements that
appear twice in the list with different select properites. (e.g. at the
root level with a lot of nested props and a second time due to a
circular reference.) We can address this, by not selecting solely by ID,
but by a combination of ID and select props.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1703 remove "combining.tmp" scratch files on startup

Such scratch files exist if a crash occured while two files were being
combined. The presence of such a file means that the process was not
finished and the file is not usable.

Prior to this fix, startup was blocked because the name of the file
couldn't be parsed. Thix fix does not alter the parsing, but actually
removes the file, knowing that it's not usable. The next combinig cycle
will simply create another one.

Note that this commit also changes the commit log switching threshold,
which helped discover this bug. Previously it would be switched at 500MB
and combined up to 1.75*500MB. While the latter number hasn't changed, a
switch now already occurs at 100MB, leading to smaller files and
slightly more frequent combining/condensing cycles. This improves
startup times after a crash, since the latest (uncondensed) log is now
smaller than it typically would be.

closes #1703

gh-659: include network refs in graphql

As outlined in #413 we aren't capable of resolving the network refs yet,
that will be tackled in #660.

Since we don't resolve yet, we also can't test this feature as a journey
test yet. However, since we have too many of those anyway, it is now
tested with a unit test (technically rather a component test) at the
local_get level. There was already an existing component test for
local.Get without network references. Having the combination of both was
a good helper to test that everything still works, both when network
peers are present and when they are not present.

Being able to run those test without any dependencies in under a  second
is a massive feedback cycle time reduction compared to the acceptance
tests which take about 10 minutes.

properties inside janusgraph, as advised by external consultants. This
means that a property like "population" would simply be called "prop_20"
in the janus schema.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1658 resolve crossreferences (multi-get)

This required changing the payload structure of some of the existing
client/api methods where we incorrectly used JSON which would not be
unmarshalled into the correct types when reading. This has been changed
to use binary methods from storobj package, which means the type parsing
is consistent with what we get from disk.

author: etiennedi
message:
parse "replace" wals into cache first on recovery

This is because the current memtable implementation does not deal well
with extremely long commit logs with a lot of duplicate entries. The
cache is a hashmap that can be used to reduce the duplicates. By only
taking into account the unique values, parsing WALs with a lot of
redundant info is much faster.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-602 prepare network pluggin, inject network to graphql build

We are now providing graphqlapi.Build with not just the db (acting as a
DatabaseResolverProvider), but also with the Network (acting as a
NetworkResolverProvider). The combination of the two is now the upated
interface ResolverProvider..

To resolve some import cycles we have moved much closer to a pluggable
entwork structure, but it is not fully pluggable yet, as we have (or
will have) a separate issue for this.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-630 resolve Network.Get where filters at new position

Basically this is just deleting a bunch of code. Previously we had to
parse the filters entirely, because we had to modify the path. It looked
somehting like

WeaviateB->Things->City->name and was placed at the level of Network.Get.

We had to rewrite this to just say Things->City->name (i.e. remove the
peer name) and inject the filter at the correct place after
Local.Get.

Now that the filters are at the level of the KindClass anyway, we just
proxy them together with everything else. So no more parsing is required
at all.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1868 properly propagate "clear links" across commit logs.

The following situation caused an issue. Imagine there are two commit
logs in chronological order:

Log 1:
- AddLink for Node/Level/Link 0/0/1
- AddLink for Node/Level/Link 0/0/2

Log 2:
- ClearLinks for Node/Level 0/0
- AddLink for Node/Level/Link 0/0/3
- AddLink for Node/Level/Link 0/0/4

It should be quite obvious that after reading all the logs back in the
correct order node 0 will have the connections [3,4] at level zero, as
there was a "clear" event in between.

However, prior to this fix we would have ended up with [1,2,3,4] because
the clear information got lost when condensing each log independently.
This fix makes sure that information that relates to changes from prior
commit logs is kept when condensing a commit log. The actual bug was
when reading (as part of condensing) as we used the clear only to clear
the links (which from the perspective of log 2 were already empty). This
led us to condensing log 2 to just "add 3, add 4", whereas the correctly
condensed log would have been "clear, add 3, add 4". This is the case
now.

To write the tests needed for this fix, it was required to add some
functional options to the commit logger to control the commit log size
thresholds. As of now these are not yet exposed to the user, but this
would also add value.

fixes #1868

Potential follow-up tasks:

1. Expose Commitlog configuration (e.g. thresholds) to user, so they can
   finetune them to their needs
2. Clean up the redundant and partly unused code, and the confusion
   between condensor/condensor2 and deserializer/deserializer2

isolated structure to describe peers.

message:
gh-761: bugfix: use custom gql fragments on cref unions

We previously assumed that the object inside the Class property
SelectionSet would either be a Field or an InlineFragment. However, if
the user uses custom fragments, we can also run into FragmentSpreads. We
are now able to deal with them as well (and recursively too)

Note that one part isn't particular pretty due to:
https://github.com/graphql-go/graphql/issues/455

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-685: replace local RWMutex (schema, connector lock) with etcd RWMutex

Generally the prepared interface (RWMutex) had to be implemted. There
were a few changes to it. Since the Lock is now a remote lock, we need
a remote connection. This in turn means that locking and unlocking can
fail. Thus the signature was changed to include error returns.

Note that this error is currently not handled well in this POC, however
an action item to replace the makeshift error handling with proper error
handling has been created.

Another major change is that we no longer use one lock, that is passed
through the entire app by reference. This is because the etcd RWMutex
works fundamentally different. The "shared" stated will be kept
server-side, this means locally the type should only be shared from a
single Lock to an Unlock. This is not yet documented well on the code
and will be added in an upcoming commit.

message:
gh-630: sketch out unit test structure for graphql builder

Right now we have an issue where duplicate schemas can lead to duplicate
object, as we found out after moving the where filter.

It's very hard right now to get feedback for that, as you basically have
to run the entire acceptance suite, with actual peers. A unit test
should be much easier to provide feedback on that. However, we first
need the changes from PR #649 becasue they substantially change the
method signarture with regards to what peers are. Previously there were
just a []string and afterwards they'll be a complex object with
individual schemas attached.

author: moretea
message:
Milestone B basics (#589)

* Introduce GraphQL interface
* Simplify error handling during schema generation
* Design GraphQL resolvers
* Remove original Graphql API
* Reverse function results of schema.Schema.FindPropertyDataType
* Fix bugs in getting classes
* Use has() instead of property() in Gremlin code
* Remove illegal date format from demo dataset.
* Import Actions too in fixture importer
* add support to fetch listClasses for a specific class
* Parse paths and value's from the filters.
* Capture panics in the spawned go routines so that Weaviate won't crash
* Split filters into multiple files
* Fix parsing references in filters
* Extract moved filter tests from local->get tests
* Remove concurrency bug from thunk in filters
* Add tests for operands & superfluous elements in filter clauses.
* Parse out nested relations from GraphQL
* Janus connector: only optionally set the variables in getClass
* Fix naming in actions acceptance tests
* Add test to patch action and set a reference
* Make it possible to patch synchronously
* Regenerated HTTP client code
* Handle float types as well during updates
  Combined with silent failures because of async-by-default behavior, this was _very_ hard to debug.
* Log stack traces in panics in the resolver go routine.
* Move presence check into the case of primitive types.
* Ref types start with a capital in GraphQL, and will therefore not be found.
* Make updates synchronous by default
* Fix importer
* Acceptance tests for GraphQL queries
* Load fixtures on Travis
* Update call to FindPropertyDataType to reflect change in ret types.
* Fix concurrency issue in building common get filters.
* Force serial creation of schema in test. This happens too in the callback

gh-1218 support aggregation for kNN classifications

Note: There is currently a mix-up of business and persistence logic as
the methods demanded by the classification UCs require there to be too
much business logic in the persistence package. However, they have been
built in a very general way, so that the logic can be moved into the
respective UCs in the future.

However, due to the nature of how much logic is touched by the
classifications, the integration tests still add a lot of value. So once
we move the business logic out, we should keep the tests and simply
replace the interface with the respective UCs so we can still test the
persistence logic related to it. This will effectively make the tests a
component test.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-609: make current schema accessible in network ping cycle

To reduce coupling a RegisterHandler was added to the network
interface, every network must implement this handler and use the getter
function that is being passed to retrieve the current schema.

This happens asynchronously (and repeatedly) which is why the "register
getter" way was chosen - so that the getter can be called later.

The signature of the passed getter is a small interface ("Schema
Getter") which tells the underlying type to provide a Schema() method
which in turn provides the current schema.

Most likely when a schema should be retrieved locking is involved,
however the network wants to stay agnostic of the internals of how a
schema provider deals with locking. In turn any type that wants to
implement the SchemaGetter, should take care of locking as part of the
Schema() method it provides.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1852 sort memtable KV pairs on read

The memtable for Map is a binary tree so it's always sorted. However,
since this is type 'Map' each "row key" holds a map. This map was
unsorted in the past. In #1832 we introduced a change that made sure
this change would always be sorted ON DISK, i.e. in the segments. It was
very natural to also keep it sorted in the memtable, as we did not have
to do any sorting when flushing. However, the performance tests on
imports that make heavy use of the inverted index had a large
performance degradation after #1832. In a test I did locally the import
time went up by over 30%.

This fix goes back to keeping the KV pairs unsorted and making each
change an append only operation. This means it now needs to be sorted in
just two places (as opposed to on every single insertion):

1. On a read query. Those should be rare on memtable, since memtables
   are mostly meant for writing. The added overhead here (minimal) is
   not a problem since it was also there before #1832
2. When flushing. Flushing is an async operation and the small overhead
   of sorting each row's Map KVs is neglible.

This new implementation has the same import speed as prior to #1832
while keeping all the runtime benefits of having the KV pairs sorted on
disk.

closes #1852

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1412 update graphql package

So, this seems to boil down to the following:

- There is an old bug in graphql-js (fixed in 2017) where the package
  ignores the isDeprecated field, but instead uses
  deprecationReason!=null to check whether a field is deprecated. This
  bug has been fixed a long time ago: https://github.com/graphql/graphql-js/pull/1035
- However, it seems various other dependencies have not updated to
  include the fix, see https://github.com/graphql-go/graphql/issues/504#issuecomment-549080559
- The graphql-go package has been (correctly) using an empty string (as
  is the default value for string) in Go if no deprecation reason is
  set. As "isDeprecated" this should not ever have mattered
- Since the bug from bullet one still seems to be present in many
  packages - as we have seen with the latest GraphiQL reason - the
  graphql-go team have now instead added a new resolver which explicitly
  sets the "deprecationReason" to null (rather than "") if not set. This
  was released in v0.7.9 which this commit udpates to
- This fixes our issue, the fields are no longer shown as deprecated in
  GraphiQL :)

message:
gh-1740 make reading vectors much more efficient

Previously we were reading (and unmarshalling!) the entire object from
disk whereas now we are only looking at the bytes relevant for the
vector. This lead to a massive speedup for pre-filling.

This commit also fixes the faulty lock that would render the entire
index unusable during the pre-filling process. It now only locks for one
iteration.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-653: (refactor) seperate concerns and clean up get_meta pkg

There were namely these issues that made working with and extending the
current package problematic:

1.) a lot of concerns were mixed up in a single file that made it
incredibly difficult to find what you were looking for. This single file
has now been split up into 9 files

2.) The code itself used unnecessarily long function and variable names
all prefixed with the name of the package, etc. This redundant info made
the code very hard to read. This has been simplified.

3.) There was some obvious low-hanging fruit regarding repition in the
big switch-case to split up by property type. This has been extracted
into a function and made much more concise.

Overall I feel like the package is now in a decent state to start
building new features on top of the exisitng code base.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-602 forward auth headers to remote instance on Network.Get

We're using an http.RoundTripper, which basically acts like a
middleware, it is called before the request is sent off. This allows us
to inject the X-API-{TOKEN,KEY} headers. We are getting those in turn
from the grahpql context.

The current setup simply calls http.DefaultTransport after the custom
RoundTripper is done. This will work as long as we only have one custom
RoundTripper. Having said that I don't currently see a reason why we
would have more than one in this particular place...

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-645: prevent invalid queries on invalid class/prop combination

The graphqlapi package is already catching cases where no classnames or
no property names are valid at all. However, there is also another case
that can only be caught in the connector (since this is the first time
we validate against the schema). If the classnames themselves are valid
and the properties as well, but they aren't combinable or don't match
the specified filter (e.g. wrong type), then we can't build a query.
This woudl previously lead to an invalid gremlin query, now we are
instead catching the errror and trying to return a helpful message to
the user.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-660: try to improve error handling for graphql response

We seem to be doing some interesting type conversion, we're first
marshalling the entire graphql response to JSON and then unmarshalling
it again into the go-swagger resopnse type. This seems to work fine for
most cases, but there is an edge cases where it breaks miserably:

When the graphql error response contains a list the path array will be
something like ["Get", "Things", 0, "foobar"]. Notice the third element
is a number, whereas all the other ones are string. Therefore this type
is defined in the graphql package as []interface{}. Howevever, we are
using OpenAPI2 with go-swagger, where variable types ("oneOf", "anyOf")
are not supported yet. Therefore the code generated by go-swagger has
the path field as []string.

The above case breaks the marhshal->unmarshal->marshal chain. Previously
it would fail silently. This commit makes sure the failure is at least
not silent anymore. Nevertheless it's not a very nice response yet. We
should improve upon this by actually converting from one response type
to the other (we can then simply convert the int to a string), rather
than using this marshal->unmarshal-marhsal magic. (#669)

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1069 don't depud based on ID alone, dedup based on all 3

An ID makes an object unique in Weaviate, but it's still not enough to
only run deduplications based on it. This is because with
SelectProperties, i.e. the user-specified instructions to traverser the
graph, there is a difference. For example if A has a reference to B of
class "BestClass" and the user asks for all references from A of type
"WorstClass", we will send a request that won't have a result. If the
user now asks for all references of clasess "WorstClass", "BestClass"
these are clearly two different requests even with the same id (since we
don't know the class yet at resolve time.) If we were to dedup only on
ID (as we did before), we'd send only the first request (asking for
WorstClass) and would end up with no results.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1798 build minimal bm25 implementation for single word query

Lots of limitations as of now:

- It currently only supports searching across a single property
- It currently only supports a single word in the query. So you can’t
  have spaces yet :smile: That’s the biggest limitation to get this
  usable and is the next big challenge
- It isn’t real BM25 yet, BM25 weights matches also by the length which
  I’m currently just faking by giving each result the same hard-coded
  length, so right now the results probably aren’t entirely correct yet,
  but they do make sense in general.
- It is not optimized in any way and will probably break at scale for
  now :slightly_smiling_face:
- It cannot yet be combined with filters

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-653: add type inspector to retrieve type of ref props

The type inspectors results are merged with the janus processors
results, so that we can neatlessly query regular getmeta info and type
info even though the come from completely different source (types com
from the schema provider (currently saved in a file), whereas GetMeta
info comes from aggregation functions in the janus db.

This type inspector is currently only used on Reference Props, however
the plan is to make it usable on every prop, so that it can inject the
'type' field when the user requests it.

author: ttsugriy
message:
Reuse sums memory for combined vector result.

Memory allocations are very expensive, so reusing it is the easiest way to speed up processing.

Even for short vectors of size 8
```
func BenchmarkCombine(b *testing.B) {
	for i := 0; i < b.N; i++ {
		CombineVectors([][]float32{
			{-0.214571, -0.605529, -0.335769, -0.185277, -0.212256, 0.478032, -0.536662, 0.298211},
			{-0.14713769, -0.06872862, 0.09911085, -0.06342313, 0.10092197, -0.06624051, -0.06812558, 0.07360107},
			{-0.18123996, -0.2089612, 0.03738429, -0.26224917, 0.18499854, -0.2620146, -0.12802331, -0.07601682},
			{-0.06659584, -0.17120242, 0.07603133, -0.07171547, 0.12537181, -0.19367254, -0.18376349, -0.05517439},
		})
	}
}
```
locally I'm getting
```
% go test ./usecases/vectorizer/ -bench=.
goos: darwin
goarch: arm64
pkg: github.com/weaviate/weaviate/usecases/vectorizer
BenchmarkCombine-8   	15384250	        78.32 ns/op
PASS
ok  	github.com/weaviate/weaviate/usecases/vectorizer	2.356s
```
instead of original
```
% go test ./usecases/vectorizer/ -bench=.
goos: darwin
goarch: arm64
pkg: github.com/weaviate/weaviate/usecases/vectorizer
BenchmarkCombine-8   	13317235	        89.44 ns/op
PASS
ok  	github.com/weaviate/weaviate/usecases/vectorizer	1.411s
```
which is ~12.5% improvement in terms of time, but it's also good for GC, especially for larger inputs.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-788: rename GetMapped... to MustGetMapped... to indicate it panics

I'm not at all happy that these methods panic, however, they are widely
used throughout the app and refactoring them all to proper error
handling is not feasible at the moment.

Calling them MustGet... is at least an idiomatic way in Go to tell the
developer that this method panics if an error occurs. This allows us to
add a safe Get... for new code at least.

This doesn't really reduce the tech debt, but at least it makes it a bit
more obvious ... and prevents us from adding even more on top of it.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1004 unresolve schema cached too deep on referenced hot cache

copy/pasted from the unresolve method:

Assume the following situation: the depth limit is two and you have a fully
cached object going two levels deep with a hot cache. Now a third object is
added referencing the original object. Since the cache of the referenced
object is hot, we don't need to do any additional resolving. However, we
can't just copy over the ref tree either, as it is already 2 levels deep. In
other words we'd end up with a three level deep cache. Over large schemas
this seemingly small inconvenience adds up to massive issues, see
https://github.com/semi-technologies/weaviate/issues/1003 and
https://github.com/semi-technologies/weaviate/issues/1004.

To remedy this, we need to parse the hot cache from the referenced object
recursively and undo any resolved cache once wewould otherwise cross the
cache boundary

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1304 fix panic on hnsw entrypoint deletion

The reason for the issue was two-fold:

1. The process of finding a new entry point takes time, if two
   concurrent delete requests came in in that same time, we could end up
   in a situation where two runs competed with one another, leading to
   unexpected beahvior. This is now prevented by a deletion lock that
   makes sure the critical parts about deletion happen sequentially.

2. While the findNewEntrypoint process is running a new insert might
   lead to an updated entryPoint. In this case the script would run
   through where there is no need. This in turn can lead to unexpected
   behavior. An "early exit" check was added to check if the entrypoint
   has changed while we are running the findNewEntrypoint script. If
   yes, then we can abort without making changes.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1569 [skip ci] WIP fix disk tree, start writing into inverted

The diskindex binary tree was extremely unbalanced leading to insane
memory requirements. This commit fixes it and makes sure it is built up
perfectly balanced. This also helps us get rid of the rather hacky
shuffling beforehand.

This commit also starts writing into the inverted index, but currently
no reading from it is done.

Note that this commit also switches various commit loggers (in both HNSW
and in the lsmkv) to be buffered io writers as the many parallel.Write()
syscalls became very problematic. However, this means that we need to
introduce forced flushes at various points, such as after completing a
batch, etc. This has not been completed yet.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-801: remove old graphql introspection based tests

Why are we removing them?

- They have been turned off (with the env var) on CI for a while, so
right now they’re not adding any value

- The prototype is no longer the source of API changes. Newer changes
were implemented in weaviate first or in some cases only in weaviate

- One of the additional benefits of the tests was checkings that Object
names don’t collide in GraphQL. We have component tests in the graphql
packages that do that now

- With most of the resolvers being implemented we also have explicit
tests to see that the GQL endpoints work correctly end-to-end, i.e. both
structure and results

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-685: always take in context from the outside

The etcdv3 client requires the ctx as one of its parameters, this is a
good pattern that we should also aim to keep up. Ideally, the restapi as
constructed by go-swagger is the creator of a context and then
everything that happens as a result of an incoming rest request should
pass along the context. We are now passsing it along for everything
schema related already, but it would be nice if everything (database
connector read/write operations, network operations, etc) in the future.

author: etiennedi
message:
add more compaction tests

This bug surfaced a gap in our compaction tests. While we already had a
fairly eloborate test setup with various operations happening during
compactions, we only verified the correctness of the result using a
cursor. Bug #3592 was specific to accessing keys directly. Cursors would
have still worked fine, therefore the tests didn't catch this bug.

Any of the newly added tests for the Map strategy would have caught the
bug, as can be proven by removing the fix which makes the tests fail.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1897 allocate new connList if more than allowed connections

How is it possible that we could ever have more connections than the
allowed maximum? It is not anymore, but there was a bug that allowed
this to happen in versions prior to v1.12.0:
https://github.com/semi-technologies/weaviate/issues/1868

As a result the length of this slice is entirely unpredictable and we
can no longer retrieve it from the pool. Instead we need to fallback
to allocating a new slice.

This was discovered as part of
https://github.com/semi-technologies/weaviate/issues/1897

message:
gh-891: use has(classId,x) intead of hasLabel(x) in Janusgraph

It seems - through trial and error - that we could identify that the
has("classId", "foo") syntax works effeciently with the ES index at
medium to large scale. Whereas the .hasLabel("foo") syntax lead to very
inefficient queries that didn't make use of ES's filtering abilities,
but instead iteration over thousands of entries to filter the results in
Janusgraph.

fixes #891

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-602 proxy filters to remote instance on Network.Get

Getting the parsed filters back to their source string was not as easy
as anticipated. The graphql-go package parses them into
map[string]interface{} which is fine to read them.

However, this presents us with two problems:

1.) When we want to "marshal" them back into the graphql format, the
format is like JSON, but is not actually JSON. The keys can't be quoted.

2.) String values are quoted, as expected, but not every value is a
string value from the perspective of the graphql schema. Operators for
example are an enum, so they also shouldn't be quoted.

This problem is currently solved with two regular expressions, to strip
the quotes off of all keys and additionally to strip the quotes off of
the values for an operator key. Not the best-scaling approach, but the
where-Filter is luckily a relatively small and predictable set of
fields. We can always look for a more elaborate solution if we actually
run into issues because of this.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-986 fix cache boundary flakyness

if the reference at the cache boundary was itself coming from cache, we
would previously blindly copy over all the content, without checking if
we would indeed cross the cache boundary and store more cache than
desired.

The flakyness derived from the fact that caching happens in no
guaranteed order, so sometimes the last item before the cache bounday
had a hot cache and sometimes it didnt'.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1272 fix additional index races leading to flakyness

In the reference batcher we previously attempted concurrent reads/writes
which aren't a problem per se. However, we could get into a situation
where we would mark a doc id as deleted before it was ever imported.
That would be problematic as doc ids on additional indices (such as
HNSW) are themselves immutable. So an import to a deleted doc id would
lead to issues, as we couldn't distuingish this from an attempt to reuse
a doc id.

As a side-effect the fix for this also made the ref-batcher slightly
more efficient, as we remove unnecessary updates on the "same" object
which was touched multiple times in one batch and therefore received
multiple increases on the doc id

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-609: in graphql api use peers schema instead of local schema

Previously we were taking a shortcut where we'd assume that every
peer has the same schema as the local version.

The commits leading up to this one made sure that a cached version of
another peer's schema is available to the graphql API. This commit now
also builds the graphql fields based on that particular schema.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-488 re-add ResolveType function for dataTypeUnionConf

The commit 7e65baa removed this particular resolver, this leads to the
dev-setup not working anymore. Weaviate is exiting with exit code one
and the error:

```
2018/09/22 13:02:28 ERROR: GraphQL schema initialization gave an error when initializing: could not build GraphQL schema, because: Union Type FlightAircraftObj does not provide a "resolveType" function and possible Type Aircraft does not provide a "isTypeOf" function. There is no way to resolve this possible type during execution..
```

This commit simply re-adds this one single resolver, so that we have a
working dev-setup again.

If the removal was intended, we probably need to replace it rather than
just removing it. For now I'm assuming the removal was accidental.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1125 prepare contextual prepare run

A prepare run is a run done before the individual per-item
classifications to provide an additional context. As part of this
prepare run we plan to fetch information that stays valid for the entire
run, such as target vectors. Additionally this is the place to calculate
tf-idf scores over all documents.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-685 manually extract context in handlers

there was a breaking change in go-swagger. In v16 you could run the
generation with --with-context and context would always be the first
argument. With v18 that option no longer exists. However, we can still
manually extract the context from the underlying HTTPRequest which we
can get throught the params.

message:
gh-1732 and an improved AND-merge mechanism

It's currently limited to exaclty two operands and is not yet used in
the production code. But at the current capabilities it is about 10x
faster than the previous implementation for merging 10k and 1M using
and:

BenchmarkAnd10k1m_Old-8                        5         200235512 ns/op
BenchmarkAnd10k1m_Optimized-8                 63          17922105 ns/op

message:
add additional tests to distributed transactions

while preparing a video for one of the upcoming features in sprint 3 I
made an assumption about our current transaction implementation leading
to tx open errors if nodes all think they were first due to network
delays. I wasn't sure if that scenario was actually covered and while we
had a similar looking test we did not have one that tested exactly this
scenario. This is why I added this to new test and to my delight it is
already passing.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-653: add totalTrue prop, introduce meta processor

The janusgraph/meta subpackage now has two components:

- The Query Builder contains everything that happens before we interact
with Janus, i.e. it uses our parsed arguments and creates a query based
on the desired props. The query is modelled to return the closest
possible result that we need for the graphQL API. Where an exact match
between our requirements for the graphQL API and what Janus returns is
not possible, the next component comes into place:

- The Query Processor sends the Query to Janus and then post-processes
the results where required. It merges props, where Janus decides to
split a map with multiplie keys into an array back into a map.
Additionally it can do arbitrary post processing per type.

This commit also adds the "totalTrue" prop to boolean props. In Janus
the counting of true/false props is one atomic unit, so we don't
seperate by counting true and false. I.e. whenever you ask for one of
the two, we also retrieve the other one. This in turn gives us the
safety to know that both will always be present. We can thus use the
post-processing step to calculate the percentages as well. Something
that I couldn't figure out how to do it Janus directly. However, this
computation is never expensive, so that shouldn't be an issue.

The atomic retrieval of both the true and false prop does however mean
that with the current logic of the query builder if both props are
specified we would retrieve both props twice (or even four times if all
four of totalTrue, totalFalse, percentageTrue, percentageFalse are set).
The next commit will include a small logic to prevent thus. Thus as of
now any prop other than the 'totalTrue' will error.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-660 don't return thunk for connecter.LocalGetClass

This seemingly simple change has quite some major implications. We were
returning a thunk previously to avoid our results bubbling up to higher
resolvers.

This behavior was a bug in go-graphql that has been fixed in v0.7.7:
https://github.com/graphql-go/graphql/issues/340 We are currently on
v0.7.5.

This commit removes the thunk and simply returns the results directly,
in order to make this work we had to introduce a new resolver at the
level of the reference field. Additionally we needed to add a
ResolveType function at the level of the classUnion (that is used to
for the reference field).

This has a nice side-effect however: We can also use the resovler to
determine whether it's a network ref or a local ref and in the case of
the former send out a query to the remote peer. (This is not in this
commit yet, this is the goal of this issue)

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1559 set graph integrity test to require at least 1 connection

As outlined in the the test's comment already it is very questionable
how much value this test adds with the use of Heuristic2 in HNSW. The
heurisitic skips "useless" connections to make sure only the key
connections are kept. In extreme cases this can mean that only one
connection is kept. At least the test will still error if nodes are
entirely unconnected which would indicate an issue.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-713 chunk batch import when sending to janus

previously the userbatch would also be the same batch we send to janus.
However, there's a limit of about 50 per batch otherwise the stack
will overflow in janus.

In a cloud setting it seemed like the constant lock getting is turning
out to be a new bottleneck. With this strategy we can increase the batch
size from the importer to say 500. We'll still be sending 10 requests of
50 to Janus, but at least we only have to get 1 instead of 10 locks.
Let's see if it helps in increasing the import speed.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-602 register callback to network for when peers change

The callback is intended to be filled with the schema udpate manager,
this way we can easily rebuild the graphql schema, whenever a new peer
is added to the network.

The callback is only called when the peers have actually changed, to
avoid constantly rebuilding the graphql api even when the network is
constant, but we received a ping for another reason.

message:
gh-1218 calculate checksum of invert index row

This will help us judge if a row has been altered since a previous read
and allow use to start caching expensive results, such as refCount
filters on classification requests.

Note there are a few debug time calculations spread out over the code,
most of those should be commented out, they will be removed before this
branch is merged into master.

Additionally this commit removes an absolutely pointless (but expensive)
sort on DocIDs. They would be turned into an allow list (which has no
order) in the next step, so this (expensive on large queries) operation
was completely pointless.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-978 don't overwrite aggregation type as numerical

previously any numerical aggregation (including count) would always set
the property type to numerical. So a non-numerical aggregation, such as
a text-based one might sometimes end up as text (if count came first,
then text props later) and sometimes as numerical if the order was
reversed.

This also lead to flakyness in tests, however, the source for the flaky
tests were not the tests themselves, but actual flaky behavior

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1569 [ci skip] fix issue with lost writes/reads for 'replace'

It was a combination of 3 issues all with similar symptopms:

1. Flushlocks were missing on various Bucket methods, thus leading to
   reads/writes into non-existing memtables, etc.
2. Various read queries only considered the active memtable or the disk
   segments, however, there at times there is a second memtable - the
   one that's currently flushing. Whenever this is active, we also need
   to read from this one, as the objects present in here are currently
   not present in either the active or already present in a loaded disk
   segments
3. There was yet another issue where a NotFound error from the
   segmentindex package was not handled correctly. Interestingly, this
   issue was quite hard to spot as it occurred non-deterministically:
   This particular code path was only touched when the bloom filter
   delivered a false positive, as the bloomfilter's 'NotFound' was
   handled correctly

Note: The fixes are included only for 'replace' strategy, but for both
regular Gets and Cursors. The other strategies will follow shortly.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-658 support 'cardinality:many' on import of network ref

For some reason the previous code used a different method to add many
refs to single refs. The single-ref code had extensive validation (for
local refs) that was skipped for many-refs.

The new code simply loops over the many refs and for each runs the same
code that we have for a single ref. This means the switch between
network and local as well as the additional validation for local refs is
now exactly the same.

The importer script previously wasn't capable of adding refs with
cardinality many. This has been fixed, but only for things, as part of
this commit.

We need to identify whether the current importer should become a
strategic tool (possibly as part of the weaviate-cli) or if it's just a
helper for our local dev setup and tests. If it's the latter it's good
the way it is, but for the former we would have to improve upon it quite
a bit.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1652 flesh out a disk based hnsw condensor

This is a rough draft, I think the approach should work, but it's not
complete. I basically picked this up between two larger tasks and plan
on continuing it next time, I'm between tasks.

It uses an index-based approach and an mmap where the index is kept in
mem and the payload is mmaped. A rough calculation showed that with a
30M hnsw graph, the index would only grow to 600MB, whereas with the old
memory-based approach the mem requirements would considerably higher:

For example, with M of 64 and even ignoring levels higher than 0, at
30M objects the requirements would have been 30GB already, so the new
solution is about 99% more memory efficient

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-602: in acceptance tests always have weaviateB and C in network

This is a rather interesting one. The acceptance tests added as part of
issue #505 re-enables the graphql test that compare an introspection of
the prototype and the actual implementation.

This also means that the exact same network instances have to be
present. Prior to this feature this was a fixed list, but now it's a
dynamic list of which instances are currently registered in the network.

As a fix, we're now adding the expected instances through our genesis
fake. (Good thing it's a fake and easy to control ;) )

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1713 gh-1716 read LSM WAL buffered, pause writing WAL while reading

So we don't accidentally create more entries to be read next time while
we're reading. Since we're only reading from disk there is no need to
write anything to disk, as we don't need the "safety". If something
fails we can just read the same file again.

The above scenario led to a weird case of duplicating the logs over and
over again when an external factor (in this case a Kubernetes
initialDelaySeconds timeout) caused restarts. This then lead to more
data being parsed on the next run, making a success less likely with
each round.

In addition we are using a buffered reader when ingesting WALs, as there
was an incredibly high amount of syscalls because of the small chunks
being read.

message:
gh-1221 fix various issues in previous delete implementations

- while the connections were cleaned up, the node itself wasn't deleted
  (yet)
- there was an issue in the selectNeighbors if a denyList was present
  the lenght was incorrect, leading to "emtpy" elements on the list
  which effectively just pointed to element 0
- the re-assign didn't skip the element to be deleted. while those new
  edges on the to-be-deleted node would be deleted in the next step
  anyway, the bi-directional edges could lead to already cleaned up
  nodes getting yet another link to the element that is being deleted

author: etiennedi
message:
TD-153: Change beacon structure to include class name (part 2)
in inverted index check old and new beacon format for backward compat

The beacon is used in the inverted index. This is because if you resolve
a ref you need to match against the beacon. Think of the following
pseudo-schema/object combination:

County(name=="Germany") -> hasCaptial -> City(name=="Berlin").

In Weaviate this would be roughly expressed as the following City:

properties: {
  "name": "Germany"
  "hasCaptial": [{
    "beacon": "weaviate://localhost/City/<id-of-Berlin>"
  }]
}

Now if a user where to filter for "Give me all the countries which a
capital named Berlin", this filter is a two step process.

1. Weaviate must identify all Cities where name=="Berlin". This is a
   simple inverted index lookup for the term "Berlin" on the City class.
   The result is a list of IDs (or a single ID in this case).

2. Now the user must find all Countries that link to the list of cities
   with the IDs from (1). This is yet another inverted index lookup. In
   this case the values for the "hasCaptial" inverted index bucket is
   the beacon format.

<-- This is the point where we get problems with two beacon formats.
Because we chose one at index time, and now we're using one at search
time. If they match, all is fine, but if they don't match, it's a
problem, as could be proven by the failing integration test that matched
for referenced values.

I was initially thinking, we could solve this by indexing both formats.
But this was a wrong line of thinking. We cannot do this because the old
format is only deprecated, so even on new imports we may end up with
both formats.

Instead I chose two look for both formats at search time. This is not
100% ideal because this introduces an additional cost. We should thus
aim to remove this backward-compatibility fix as soon as we can
guarantee that we will have no more old beacons, such as in v2.0.0.

Basically the fix now does a lookup in step two for two values chained
using an "OR" operation. Instead of looking for just one format, we are
now looking for

weaviate://localhost/City/<id-of-Berlin>
OR
weaviate://localhost/<id-of-Berlin>

Always one of the two should match.

Please also note the TODO-comment I added to the ref-filter integration
tests. This test currently only uses the old format, but I think it
would be nice to change it so it uses a mix of old and new formats, so
that we have a good guarantee that mixing formats works well.

author: etiennedi
message:
[skip ci] gh-1148 add primitive vector cache for hnsw index

The hnsw index is most efficient if the vectors are held in memory.
However, we cannot assume that the user has infinite memory available.
Thus we can limit it with a simple cache. The cache is primitive in the
sense that it simply gets purged when it's full.

As part of the spikes preceeding this we have also investigated smarter
caches, that would purge entries with fewer recent hits first, etc.
However the orcehstration of that turned out to be more expensive than
the benefit it provided.

The cost of fillign the cache is not astronomically high, so this seems
to be a good solution for now.

The size is currenlty hard-coded to 10k items. This should get us far
enough on small datasets and still should have a decent performance even
if it gets purged a lot on medium sized set.

To support large sets (where it's a given that cluster nodes are not
tiny) ideally we'd make the limits dynamic. If there is still
allocatable RAM (keeping in mind that the key/value store is also
mmapped and needs mem), it could grow. This would especially make it
easier on datasets with a lot of indices/shards where we can't easily
predict which index/shard will take the highest load.

author: redouan-rhazouani
message:
Improve implementation of the visited list (fixes, new memory allocation strategy) (#2023)

TD-193: Improve memory allocations using a new strategy

Fix memory leaks

Improve implementation of the list pool and RC

This PR makes the visited list faster not necessarily reducing the amount of used memory.

This is because the same approach (set as []int8 ) is used as before but the implementation has been changed

The main advantage of the new implementation are:

The list is compact because it can be hold as a value (no pointer needed).
It reduces the number of times the list needs to be resized because it uses variable growth. This is the major difference to the current implementation which use fix growth (1000 bytes). This will come in handy when inserting huge number of objects.
Pool.Borrow() uses LIFO approach to manage lists and to prevent from memory leaks

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1616 exchange json parser and remove unnecessary allocations

A lot of reading was done using binary.LittleEndian.Read() which led to
allocations we didn't need. By not using a reader, but accessing the
slice directly, we can keep a lot of short-term variables on the stack.
This removes a lot of unnecessary allocs.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1334 keep doc id on batch ref updates

They are a special case because we can be sure that no inverted index
clean ups are required (as we only add to it) and no vector indices
require udpating as a ref does not alter the vector position.

This allows for a considerably faster import. The news-pub dataset which
I used for testing while development was imported in around 1:45min
instead of the previous 2:30min.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-658 fix broken acceptance test for actions

Prior to the the change from the previous commit we had never used a
patch with multiple refs (i.e. array type) because the importer only
supported a single ref.

In order to get it working we had to change one type assertion were
previous code assumed a pointer type, but on a multi-ref patch we got a
non-pointer type.

However, this broke the case of put where we indeed get a pointer type,
so now we have a very small logic to deref the pointer type only if needed.

In the next step, the Merge API will be enriched with structures for
Merging to actually distinguish it from Get

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-986 order cache invalidation by path length

Previously we would invalidate all affected classes at once. However,
this means that in rare cases ES would return a class matching a long
path (e.g. n=5) before a short path (e.g. n=1). If a refresh period
now happens when the long path was already updated, but the short path
wasn't, we would end up with the long rebuilding its cache before the
short has been invalidated. This means that we'd rebuild the long path
cache with the old/stale/uncahnged inner data. (Essentially we had a
race)

This resulted in some test flakyness as most of the times a refresh
cycle didn't happen to be exactly between two invalidation updates - but
sometimes they were. By fixing the underlying root problem, we seem to
have removed all flakyness around it as well.

This commit makes sure they are random as to prevent having to perform
massive exhaustive searches on them

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-647: add acceptance test, change priority when creating predicates

See this inline comment, for we have changed the order/priority of
assembling the predicates:

Note that we are first iterating over the term, then over the prop. This
is because the terms are already an ordered list where the match with
the highest certainty is the first item. Janus also imposes a limit, so
we need to abort if we get too many predicates. Assuming we have 20
props and 20 matches, by iterating over the matches first, this way,
we'll be able to cover about the 6 best matches on all props. If we
split the order of iteration, we would cover all matches, but completely
ignore 14 out of 20 props.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1219 mark with tombstone and ignore nil-vector

This way we have some self-healing abilities, the current
search/neighbor connection will not be interrupted and by marking the
deleted node with a tombstone we make sure that the
tombstone-cleaner-upper-and-nodes-reassigner will pick it up in the next
cycle

author: etiennedi
message:
improve cache locality in pq distance lut

Collapse two-dimensional slices into single dimensionsal. This serves
three purposes:

1. Improved cache locality during lookups because the memory is
   contiguous
2. Fewer allocations (no. of allocs) because we only allocate 1 slice,
   no longer 128+ sub-slices
3. Fewer allocations (size) because we save on a lot of unnecessary
   slice headers

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-658: on import validate (and accept) network refs

This runs the whole validation process including whether the network
peer exists and whether the class on that peer exists. This might lead
to some timing inssues in the acceptance tests because we don't know
whether the network will be registered yet, by the time the import runs.
So we could consider importing the class with the reference only when
the test has reported that the network is ready.

As of now the graphql tree creation still fails because it can't handle
the network class ref.

message:
gh-1866 reuse connection list in searchLayerByVector

Also make sure that no more goroutines are spawned in a thread than
there are CPU cores. This way we don't create so many visited lists, but
rather just one per core. This prevents memory spikes at large setups
with large batch sizes.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-730: merge dev and prod build process

Previously the c11y inside the weaviate container was a deciding factor
between using a dev or production image. Now we can finally get rid of
this big anti-pattern. Since configuring the contextionary is simply
pointing it to the right URL now, there is no more need to have separate
proceses. Instead we can just use one image for weviate and change the
contextionary image as we like

This simplifies the setup quite a bit. (And should lead to a massive
reduction in build times)

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1908 reuse parsed collection node buffers (150GB->126GB)

This commit allows parsing a collection node into a reusable buffer.
Additonally it supports a reusable segment cursor for collections that
makes use of this functionality. As a final step this new cursos is used
as part of the map compactor.

This commit is the final step on this allocation reduction journey. Out
of the remaining 126GB of allocations maybe only 2-3 GB are left from
the map compactor. However, these also include things that stay on the
heap such as bloom filters. I would recommend to focus elsewhere
(memtable, flush cycle) etc for further improvements.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-658: adhere to 'localhost' convention in local ref in acc test

As mentioned previously we are now enforcing the convention that a local
reference must always have 'localhost' as the location URL. Previously
it was also allowed to match the hostname under which the weaviate
instance would start up. So this means previosly 127.0.0.1 was also
allowed for a local reference.

We still had some test that used the exact host, i.e. 127.0.0.1. This
commit should replace all of them with localhost and fix the broken
tests.

validate whether all the required fields for a particular method are
set. This should happen in the respective packages.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-715: replace remaining comoposite indices with mixed index

For this we need to make sure that we index string props either as
STRING or TEXTSTRING, meanin that we can also use the mixed index for
"exact-match" style searches. Previously whenever the gremlin query was
`eq(string)` it would fall back to a composite index even if other
paramaters where included that would have been better answered with the
mixed index.

We now only have a single composite index left: for uuid - guaranteeing
to make uuid unique, somethign that a mixed index cannot do.

This should improve performance at scale considerably.

Note that indexing with the external index is not always instant, so we
had to adjust some tests which were implicitly assuming an atomic
create-and-index process. They are now waiting for a created thing or
action to actually become available on the index before performing
further operations on them.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-647: move GetPropsOfType from schema manager to schema

Putting it into the manager was an incorrect assumption before. The
manager is just responsible for coordinating and storing changes.
However, all other read-only queries that access the schema are on the
schema-type itself. This way they can easily be consumed in the existing
connectors. Whereas the schema manager might not be accessible from
within the connectors.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-685: reenable schema manager tests

Previously they needed a temporary file directory to write to the disk.
Since changing from the local implementation to the etcd implemenation
we previously weren't able to run this test anymore. As part of the POC
this was acceptable, but now when moving to production-quality code, we
need it again of course.

I saw two options:
a) Turn this into an integration test
b) Fake etcd.

Since we were using only two methods on the etcd client (Get() and
Put()) faking was the much cheaper option. The fake is a very simple
map[string]string as a KeyValue store which gives us everything we need
to make the tests pass again :)

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-644: resolve json.Number correctly in graphQL api

Since the results are proxied from another peer and we use the
go-graphql client, the numberes are typed as json.Number. This commit
makes sure that every conceivable (unless I missed one in my tests)
GetMeta field is able to deal with the json.Number type.

The nice side-effect is that we have a component test now that tests a
lot of edge cases, i.e. almost all possible properties. This can
potentially also prevent us from unrelated regressions.

gh-660: no longer return thunk in connector.LocalGetMeta

The original intend of the thunks was to enable parallelism. We want to
keep this idea, but the thunk can always be created in the
graphql.Resolve() methode in the graphqlapi package. The connectors do
not have to know of the concept of thunks, their concern should simply
be to resolve based on the given input.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1069 use smarter request cacher

Instead of recursively contacting the backend, we are checking for the
first level of references and then fetching all desired refs in a single
request. For my test case this already got the response time down from
350ms to 60ms for a single level request.

Note that resolving multiple levels is not possible yet. And that the
code requires quite some cleanup.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-653: enable support for where filters

Thanks to the way we built the filter query builder in a very isolated
and pluggable fashion in #680, we could simply plug them in right here.

Interestingly the first (explorative) tryout of the filters highlighted
a small issue that I previously hadn't thought about. To calculate the
percentage of bool values we rely on having a count for true and false.
However, while using the filteres I narrowed down the result sets of
Cities where all results would have 'isCapital == true'. This led to an
error in the meta aggregator:

  got a successful response from janus, but could not merge the results:
  could not postprocess 'map[string]interface
  {}{"boolGroupCount":map[string]interface {}{"true":1}}': boolProps did
  not contain any info about no of props which are 'false', got
  'map[string]interface {}{"true":1}

However, filters or not, it is of course completely viable to have
result sets where all boolean props are true, or all boolean props are
false.

So, we have to introduce a fix for this in an upcoming commit.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-609: in acceptance test runner remove orphans on d-c down

We have two docker-compose files in this repo. So if you start up the
dev one and then the test one it won't be able to do a poper
docker-compose down, because some containers are running in the same
network that are not specified in the current compose file.

Docker-compose considers those containers "orphans". By default stopping
a network with orphans errors, as they might still be in use. We can
circumvent that by specifying the `--remove-orphans` flag which means
all orphaned containers in the current network wil be stopped as well.

This gives us the ability to create a clean slate before our test runs.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-831 fix issues with deleting properties

Previously we would first try to remove the property from our own cached
(and stored in etcd) schema representation, then remove it from the db.
The latter would fail because it tries to query to former about the
property.

This would leave us in an inconsistent state, creating all kinds of
other fallout.

While fixing this, we discovered that plenty of other endpoints in both
REST and GQL would fail after a property was deleted. This should also
be addresesd with this now.

closes #831

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-685: extensively document behavior of distributed RWMutex

With a local Mutex it's very important to pass it by reference, so we
always operate on exactly the same lock. For this distributed lock using
etcd it's the other way round. The lifespan of a Mutex type should only
be from Lock() to Unlock() or from RLock() to RUnlock().

This commit adds extensive documentation including examples of why not
paying attention to this is problematic.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-645: error in graphql resolver if c11y search returned no results

The two special cases that we can run into are if either there is no
class found or we have classes, but don't have any properties to search
on. This would lead to errors down the line in the connector. However,
instead of having to handle this special case in every single connector
we're handling it in the earliest possible layer now, i.e. in the
graphQL resolver.

This means that the database connector now has the guarantuee that there
will always be at least one class and one property to search for. This
gives now guarantuee that they "match" though. I.e. it could still be
possible that we get classA and property classB.propertyFoo back.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-653: enable <refProp>.count

I must have accidentally ticked that off on my todo list, because it was
ticked off but when recording a demo video I realized that the feature
was never built. It is now.

Note that there's currently a bit of confusion about capitalization of
refProps, such as "InCountry". On user-facing parts we have them
uppercased, but on schema imports (and therefore in the database) they
are lowercased like "inCountry". I don't really see a reason for that
and it currently leads to some ugly transformations, such as
string.Title() being used, when displaying the prop and untitle(), i.e. a
custom untitling function, being used when taking in user input.

I want to discuss and potentially fix this confusion as part of #677.

regular filter-only searches we still need to make sure they are
removed.

author: etiennedi
message:
fix broken if condition

The original condititon was interpreted as

- either the bucket is nil && the prop is "create"
- or the prop is "update"

This lead to false positives if the prop was "update". It is now fixed
to mean that

- when the bucket is nil
- and the prop is either "create" or "update"

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-645: build simple schema search onto contextionary

Previously the "search" interface on the contextionary would simply be
to run a kNN search on it. however, this would mean that you would
handle raw words and would not have any indication of whetehr they are
class names or properties or just words in the contextionary.

The schema search adds that abstraction and makes it much easier to use
from the rest of the app, where no knowledge of the internals of the
contextionary should be required.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-1272 [ci skip] fix merge issue where vector was ignored

The merge implementation relied on the fact that - in the old
implemtation - an explicit vector update was the only thing that could
lead to a new doc id. Now that every update leads to a new doc id, the
old implementation would sometimes write into the vector index with a
nil-vector

Note that we currently still have the same issue on the batch-reference
which also relied on the fact that a ref update would never alter the
vector position. It is marked with a TODO and needs to be fixed before
the completion of this issue.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-658: validate remote kind exists on import

To make this work with the dev-setup we are again relying on the
weaviate_b_fake which is simply the graphql prototype. In order to pass
validation the prototype will respond for exactly one "Country" with a
specific ID.

Additionally, we are starting to uphold the convention that a local
reference must contain 'localhost' (without ports) as the host,
regardless of what network address it's actually running or reachable
on. The logic is now simply "localhost" == local ref. All other hosts,
even 127.0.0.1 represent a network ref, referenced by peer name (!), not
actual host or FQDN.

message:
gh-653: extrapolate missing bool data if all are of the same value

After introducing filter (see previous commit message for details) we
found out that if we have only boolean props which are either all true
or all false, we miss data about the opposite value (which is zero in
this case). This commit makes sure we don't error, but instead
extrapolate the data we're missing.

author: etiennedi
message:
Improve Dev-Server Script

This PR aims to improve the DX for the dev server script:

* global variables are no longer hard-coded, they are taken from the
  environment if not set. If not provided defaults are used.
* repetition is removed among the invidivual configurations by moving
  all variables that are the same for every config to the global level

This change is non-breaking and running the script without setting any
env vars has the same effects as before. However, you can now customize
it. For example to change the log format to JSON and to run with a
different data path you can simply run:

```
LOG_LEVEL=json DATA_PERSISTENCE_PATH=./some-other-path \
  tools/dev/run_dev_server.sh local-no-modules
```

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-713: POC (!) try different batch import strategy

Previously we would parallelize batch requests by spawning different
goroutines per item and send one request to janus. At scale this leads
to a massive HTTP overhead and a lot of network traffic.

This POC tries to send a single request per batch to the connector which
includes all vertices to be added.

WARNING: This is very much POC code that is NOT production ready. If it
proves to work well, it will get imporoved.

Things that are currently keeping this from beign production ready are:
- only doing this for things, actions is still the old way
- we don't return meaningful data
- validation results are completely ignored

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-653: support int props: calculate count

Previoulsly we pretended that every prop would always be a bool, this
enabled us to start quickly and not have to worry about analyzing the
type of the individual property.

Since we have now added the second type (int) this switching was
required and thus added. So far we only support "count" as a statistical
analysis prop, but have a good base to add others as well.

Please note that the way we aggregate ints leads to a special case when
only one prop is requested:

  just one analysis prop is a special case, because in multiple cases we
  are using select(<1>,<2>, ...<n>), this means we will receive a map
  that has the selections as keys. However, if we only ask for a single
  prop, Gremlin doesn't see a need to return a map and simply returns
  the primitive value. This will of course either break our
  post-processing or will not have the format the graphql API expects.
  We thus need to add an additional as().project().by() step to wrap the
  primtive prop in a map - but only if it's only a single analysis prop.

author: etiennedi
message:
delete new files when dropping a segment, fix remaining tests

The drop command is also called as part of compactions, so we can now
garuantee that no old state is left after compacting two segments.
However, currently we are also relying on the first segment init after
the compaction to build all files again. This works, but can probably be
optimized further:

My current assumption is that when two segments are merged, the cnas of
the existing segments can simply be added. Right now we would
re-calculate them at segment init which can be very expensive on large
segments.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-693: build query to aggregate numerical props with count

so far, we can only aggregate the count, nothing else yet. Additionally,
we are currently pretending that grouping is always done by primitive
props. Additionally no post-processing is happening yet, however
post-processing will be necessary as we are currently returning
aggregation keys such as "prop_18__count", this is because they have to
be unique in our gremlin query across all props, but will repeat in the
graphql api.

These limitations will be overcome with future commits.

Additionally, please note that we already have edge case handling for
queries with just a single property and queries with just a single
aggregator. The reaon for why these are edge cases are extensively
documented in database/connectors/janusgraph/aggregate/query_builder.go

message:
gh-627: udpate user-facing p2p documentation

It was outdated in two ways:

- It showed an old network architecture model, where a genesis did
exist, but wasn't a standalone product. But rather a peer would turn
into a genesis and then turn into a regular peer. This has been
completely rewritten now to indicate that the gensis is what makes the
network a hybrid-p2p network.

- It showed outdated configuration options for an unknown field `p2p`
in the local configuration. This has been corrected to use the correct
field `network` now.

author: etiennedi
message:
gh-680: spike out happy path for a single primitive filter

In order to do so, the previous filter implementation has been removed
entirely. To my surprise not a single high-level test fails because of
this. :(

What does this hard-coded POC do?
- always assume there is just a single filter condition
- always assume the filter condition is "lessthan"
- always assume the filter prop and its value is a number
- completely ignore reference props

If all these conditions are met, we actually have a working
implementation. These means the spike was a success and we now have a
relatively clear path ahead to build working filters for
- all primitive props
- combinations of primitive prop filters

Since this is a relatively well-isolated concern, I will build the new
logic in a sub-package and make sure the new code is test-driven, thus
hopefully also improving the quality of the current implemenation.
